'''Additive genetic effects''' occur when two or more genes source a single contribution to the final [[phenotype]], or when [[allele]]s of a single gene (in [[heterozygote]]s) combine so that their combined effects equal the sum of their individual effects.<ref>{{citation |author=Rieger, R. |author2=Michaelis, A. |author3=Green, M.M. |year=1968  |title=A glossary of genetics and cytogenetics: Classical and molecular |publisher=Springer-Verlag |location=New York |isbn=9780387076683 }}</ref><ref>http://www.medterms.com/script/main/art.asp?articlekey=25508</ref> Non-additive genetic effects involve [[Dominance (genetics)|dominance]] (of alleles at a single [[Locus (genetics)|locus]]) or [[epistasis]] (of alleles at different loci).

